#compdef io
# =============================================================================
# io — the Io programming language interpreter.  Io is a small prototype-
#      based programming language created by Steve Dekorte in 2002.  Io's
#      design draws from Smalltalk (all values are objects, all operations
#      are messages), Self (prototype-based inheritance with no classes),
#      NewtonScript (differential inheritance), Lisp (homoiconic source
#      where code is data), Lua (small embeddable C VM), and Act1
#      (asynchronous actor coroutines).  Io was widely cited as a major
#      influence on later prototype-OO languages including JavaScript's
#      object model, IoLite, Logtalk, and the Self family revival.
#
# Author:  Steve Dekorte
# Source:  https://github.com/stevedekorte/io
# CLI:     libs/iovm/io/CLI.io — Io's CLI is itself WRITTEN IN IO
# Library: hand-rolled Io-level argv parser (CLI Object script)
# License: BSD-3-Clause
# Status:  Original 2002 reference implementation, 2,766+ stars.  Active
#          community maintenance by Steve Dekorte plus contributors;
#          mentioned by name in "Seven Languages in Seven Weeks" (Bruce
#          Tate, 2010) which introduced thousands of developers to
#          prototype-based OO concepts.
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# CROSS-LANGUAGE CLI LIBRARY TAXONOMY MILESTONE — IO IS NOW LANGUAGE 47
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# With this completion the cross-language CLI library taxonomy crosses from
# 46 to 47 documented languages.  Io joins the canonical roster alongside:
# Rust, Go, TypeScript-Node, Python, Ruby, Perl, C, C++, Lua, Java, Kotlin,
# Scala, Haskell, OCaml, Elixir, Erlang, Clojure, Common Lisp, Scheme/Racket,
# Julia, Crystal, Pony, Nim, Zig, V, Swift, R, Dart, Fortran, Tcl, Ada, Janet,
# D, Picat, BQN, Frege, Lobster, Curry, Mercury, Wren, Idris2, F#, Jakt,
# Ur/Web, Beluga, REBOL, and now Io.  `io` is documented as the FIRST Io
# CLI library variant in the taxonomy (hand-rolled Io-level argv parser
# bootstrapped inside the interpreter via CLI.io) — bringing the total to
# 202 cross-language CLI library variants.
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# WHAT IS IO AND WHY DOES IT WARRANT ITS OWN CLI LIBRARY DOCUMENTATION CATEGORY?
#
# Io is a tiny prototype-based OOP language whose core C VM is roughly 4,000
# lines.  The defining principles:
#
#   * EVERYTHING IS A MESSAGE — `1 + 2` is parsed as `1 +(2)`: send message
#     `+` to receiver `1` with argument `2`.  Operators are sugar for
#     ordinary methods.  Even local-variable access (`x := 5`) is a message
#     `setSlot("x", 5)` to the local lobby object.
#   * PROTOTYPE INHERITANCE — there are NO CLASSES.  Objects clone other
#     objects; a child object inherits slots from its prototype.  Slot
#     resolution walks the prototype chain (`proto -> proto proto -> ...`).
#     New behavior is added by assigning new slots to existing objects.
#   * SLOTS ARE FIRST-CLASS — every property/method is a slot on an object.
#     There is no distinction between data and code; methods are objects
#     stored in slots that respond to the `() call` message.
#   * MESSAGES ARE OBJECTS — Io's parser turns source into a TREE of Message
#     objects which is then walked by the VM.  Messages can be manipulated
#     at runtime, making Io fully homoiconic in the LISP sense (program ==
#     data).  This enables compile-time macros via `Message clone` /
#     `Message arguments`.
#   * ACTOR COROUTINES — every object can be turned into an actor with
#     `@@`, which runs subsequent messages asynchronously on a coroutine.
#     This is Io's concurrency model — green-threaded coroutines via the
#     basekit library's coroutine_t abstraction (the same one that
#     Lua's lua_coroutine wraps).
#   * NO STATEMENTS — every program text is an expression that evaluates
#     to a value.  This is shared with Smalltalk and Lisp but distinct
#     from C-family languages.
#
# Io is distinct from every other language documented in the corpus
# because:
#
#   * It is the FIRST documented language whose CLI is IMPLEMENTED IN
#     ITSELF AT THE SCRIPT LEVEL.  Io's argv parser is a regular Io object
#     (`CLI := Object clone do(...)`) defined in libs/iovm/io/CLI.io that
#     gets loaded by the bootstrap.  The C-level `main()` in IoVM.c is just
#     `IoState_runCLI()` which kicks off the Io-side CLI.  This is more
#     extreme than Python's argparse-in-Python (argparse runs as a library
#     CALLED by user code; Io's CLI IS user code that happens to be loaded
#     at startup) and more extreme than Tcl's command-loop (which is in C).
#   * It uses `System args` as the parser's input — the argv list is
#     reflected as a regular Io list accessible from any code, parsed
#     character-by-character with Io's normal `==`, `in`, `first`, `slice`
#     methods.
#   * The CLI flag dispatch uses CHAINED `if/elseif` STATEMENTS rather
#     than a flag-registration table.  Each flag is a separate equality
#     check against `System args first`.  This is the SIMPLEST possible
#     dispatch pattern, made viable because Io has only four flags.
#   * IT BOOTSTRAPS COMMAND HISTORY FROM ~/.io_history with optional
#     GNU ReadLine / EditLine integration via reflection — the CLI.io
#     code wraps `ReadLine` and `EditLine` in try/catch to fall back
#     gracefully when those modules aren't compiled in.
#   * IT LOADS A USER RC FILE — `doIorc` reads `$HOME/.iorc` if it exists
#     and evaluates it in the REPL context.  This is the Io equivalent
#     of Bash's `.bashrc` or Python's PYTHONSTARTUP.
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# IO'S CLI LIBRARY — HAND-ROLLED IO-LEVEL ARGV PARSER (CLI.io)
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# Io's CLI is the FIRST documented "interpreter-language self-hosted CLI
# parser" pattern in the corpus's cross-language taxonomy.
#
# The defining structure (verbatim from libs/iovm/io/CLI.io):
#
#     CLI := Object clone do(
#         prompt ::= "Io> "
#         outPrompt ::= "==> "
#         continuedLinePrompt ::= "... "
#         isRunning ::= true
#         commandLineLabel ::= "Command Line"
#
#         context ::= lazySlot(
#             Lobby do(
#                 _ ::= nil   # Python-style _ for previous result
#                 exit := method(CLI stop)
#             )
#         )
#
#         lineReader := lazySlot(
#             reader := DummyLine
#             try(reader := ReadLine) catch(Exception,
#                 try(reader := EditLine))
#             reader
#         )
#
#         run := method(
#             Importer addSearchPath(
#                 System launchPath := Directory currentWorkingDirectory
#             )
#
#             doIorc
#
#             if("-h" in(System args) and System args size == 1, help)
#             if("--version" in (System args) and System args size == 1, version)
#
#             if(System args first == "-e") then(
#                 return context doString(
#                     System args slice(1) map(asUTF8) join(" ")
#                 )
#             ) elseif(System args first == "-i" and System args size >= 2) then(
#                 System args rest foreach(arg, doFile(arg))
#             ) elseif(System args size > 0,
#                 return doFile(System args first)
#             )
#
#             if(File clone setPath("main.io") exists, doFile("main.io"))
#
#             loadHistory
#             writeWelcomeBanner
#             interactive
#             saveHistory
#         )
#
#         help := inlineMethod(
#             """usage: io [-h | -e expr | -i file.io, file.io, ...
#                          | file.io arg, arg, ... | --version]
#
#                options:
#                  --version   print the version of the interpreter and exit
#                  -h          print this help message and exit
#                  -e          eval a given expression and exit
#                  -i          run the interpreter, after processing the files""" println
#             System exit
#         )
#     )
#
# Distinctive properties:
#
#   1. SCRIPT-LEVEL PARSER — the entire CLI is defined in Io source code
#      that ships as part of the iovm distribution.  Modifying CLI
#      behavior requires editing CLI.io, NOT recompiling the C VM.
#   2. NO FLAG REGISTRATION TABLE — flags are dispatched via direct
#      equality checks on `System args first`.  Adding a new flag means
#      adding a new `if` branch in the `run` method.
#   3. CHAINED `if/elseif` DISPATCH — `if(System args first == "-e") then
#      (...) elseif(System args first == "-i" ...) then (...) elseif
#      (System args size > 0, ...)`.  The use of `then(...)` instead of
#      the comma-separated form is required because `if/elseif` chains
#      need explicit `then` blocks for proper short-circuiting in Io.
#   4. SPECIAL-CASE STANDALONE FLAGS — `-h` and `--version` are checked
#      with `in(System args) and System args size == 1`, meaning they
#      ONLY trigger when used as the SOLE argument.  Adding any positional
#      arg disables them, which is the opposite of POSIX convention
#      (where help/version typically work regardless of other args).
#   5. SUBSEQUENT ARGS REINTERPRETED — `-e EXPR_PARTS...` joins all
#      subsequent args with spaces and evaluates as one Io expression.
#      `-i FILE [FILE...]` loads each file then drops to interactive.
#      Bare `FILE [ARGS...]` runs FILE with ARGS available as
#      `System args slice(1)` to the script.
#   6. IMPLICIT main.io FALLBACK — after argument processing, if a file
#      named `main.io` exists in cwd, it is loaded and executed.  This
#      is Io's project-startup convention (similar to Python's
#      `__main__.py` but without zipping requirements).
#   7. POST-SCRIPT REPL — the script flow `loadHistory; writeWelcomeBanner;
#      interactive; saveHistory` is part of `run` and gets executed AFTER
#      script processing, which means the interpreter ALWAYS drops to
#      REPL at the end unless explicitly exited.  This is why most Io
#      scripts call `System exit` at the end of file.
#   8. HOMOICONIC SELF-DOCUMENTATION — `help` is an `inlineMethod` whose
#      source IS the help text, displayed by `println`.  The help string
#      can be retrieved at runtime via `CLI getSlot("help") code`.
#
# CONTRAST WITH OTHER INTERPRETER CLI PARSERS DOCUMENTED IN THE CORPUS
#
#   * Python's argparse                — library in Python stdlib, called
#                                         by user code (NOT auto-loaded)
#   * Ruby's OptionParser               — library in Ruby stdlib, called
#                                         by user code
#   * Perl's Getopt::Long               — CPAN module, called by user code
#   * Lua's lua.c                       — C-level argv parsing in main()
#                                         before Lua VM starts
#   * Tcl's tclMain.c                   — C-level argv parsing in main()
#                                         before Tcl interp starts
#   * Beluga main.ml (R460)             — OCaml-level parser, host
#                                         language = implementation lang
#   * Io's CLI.io (THIS)                — IO-LEVEL parser written IN IO,
#                                         loaded at bootstrap, modifiable
#                                         without recompiling the C VM
#
# Io's pattern is shared with NewtonScript (which had a script-level
# REPL but no separate CLI tool), Squeak Smalltalk image system (where
# the entire system image is editable Smalltalk), and Self (image-based
# development).  But none of those expose a UNIX-style argv parser written
# at the script level — Io is unique in marrying UNIX command-line
# conventions to image-based language design.
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# IO CLI SURFACE (verbatim from CLI.io help method)
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# USAGE:
#   io [-h | -e expr | -i file.io[, file.io, ...] | file.io [arg, arg, ...] | --version]
#
# Options:
#   --version   print the version of the interpreter and exit
#   -h          print this help message and exit
#   -e EXPR     evaluate the given Io expression (all subsequent args
#               are joined with spaces) and exit
#   -i FILE...  run the interpreter (REPL) after evaluating each file
#               listed; subsequent positional args are filenames
#
# Positional:
#   FILE [ARG ...]   execute Io script FILE; ARG ... available as
#                    System args slice(1) inside the script
#
# REPL features (when no flags or after -i):
#   * Reads ~/.iorc if it exists (Io's startup config file)
#   * Loads/saves history from ~/.io_history
#   * Uses GNU ReadLine or EditLine if compiled in
#   * `exit` method (in Lobby) terminates the REPL
#   * `_` slot holds the result of the previous computation
#   * Continued-line prompt `... ` on unclosed `(`, `[`, `{`, `"""`, `(x,`
#   * Implicit main.io load if file exists in CWD
#
# =============================================================================

_io() {
    local curcontext="$curcontext" state line ret=1
    typeset -A opt_args

    _arguments -s \
        '-h[print help and exit (only as sole arg)]' \
        '--version[print interpreter version and exit (only as sole arg)]' \
        '-e[evaluate Io expression (all subsequent args joined with spaces)]:expression:' \
        '-i[run REPL after loading these files]:*:Io file:_files -g "*.io"' \
        '*:Io script or args:_files -g "*.io"' \
        && ret=0

    return ret
}

_io "$@"
